Currently the deployment enviroments are static. You have to setup them and name them. Only then you can use deployment functionality in Bitbucket Pipelines.

That does not scale very much when using automatic testing enviroment per branch or pull request. For example we have containerized testing enviroment for each branch (eg. [http://internal.company.com/feature/JIRA-1234-introduced-dynamic-deploy-env).] Each branch has its own testing enviroment so it can be easilly tested before the pull request gets merged. I believe this is a pretty common work flow and it should be supported by Bitbucket.

I would like to have dynamic deployment enviroments, so I dont need to setup them ahead. So I could do something like following:
{code:java}
- step:
     name: Deploy branch
     deployment: ${BITBUCKET_BRANCH}
     script:
        - echo "Deploying...";{code}

Please improve Bitbucket API documentation and provide example of the POST JSON body for creating deployment environment within a repository using Bitbucket open API: 

[https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/environments/#post]

Specify that we only support the "name" for already existing environments and highlight it as a requirement. 

When user is trying to create a deployment environment with the name that doesn't already exist we respond with: 
{code:java}
{"key": "deploy-service.request.validation-error","message": "The request body contains invalid properties","arguments": {"environment.environment_type.name": "Unknown environment type."}
{code}
*Here is the example of the POST request that end users can use for reference, until the public documentation is updated:* 
{code:java}
{"deployment_gate_enabled": false,
"rank": 0,
"hidden": false,
"type": "deployment_environment",
"slug": "staging123",
"environment_type": {
"type": "deployment_environment_type",
"name": "Staging",
"rank": 1
},
"name": "Staging123"
}

OR 
{
"hidden": false,
"type": "deployment_environment",
"slug": "feature1234-6",
"environment_type": {
"type": "deployment_environment_type",
"name":"Production",
"rank": 0
},
"name": "Feature1234-6"
}
{code}

On page [https://www.atlassian.com/git/tutorials/using-branches/git-merge], section _Merging_ you write:

{color:#4d4d4d}Once the previously discussed "preparing to merge" steps have been taken a merge can be initiated by executing {color}{{git merge}}{color:#4d4d4d} where {color}{color:#4d4d4d} is the name of the branch that will be merged into the receiving branch.{color}

The name of the branch seems to be missing (twice).

h3. Issue Summary
The following API [https://developer.atlassian.com/bitbucket/api/2/reference/resource/repositories/%7Bworkspace%7D/%7Brepo_slug%7D/default-reviewers/%7Btarget_username%7D] endpoint does not work when UUID is passed to the field "target_username"

h3. Steps to Reproduce
Step 1: try to fetch default reviewer details using
 "/2.0/repositories/ \{workspace}/\{repo_slug}/default-reviewers/\{target_username}"
 Step 2: Provide UUID of the target user instead of username

h3. Expected Results

Default reviewer details should be shown
h3. Actual Results
 * Error:*
{code:java}
{
"type": "error",
"error":

{ "message": "Resource not found" }
}
{code}

h3. Workaround

The existing API works fine for username. While using the same API with UUID of the target_user, use a filter for UUID
{code:java}
2.0/repositories/ \{workspace}/\{repo_slug}/default-reviewers?q=uuid="{Target_user_UUID}"
{code}

Currently, the $BITBUCKET_PIPELINE_UUID environment variable sets its value with curly braces wrapping it, like so:
{code}
{abcd12-4321-ffff-a234-1111111111aa}
{code}
This is a default variable as per https://support.atlassian.com/bitbucket-cloud/docs/variables-and-secrets/

This feature request is to remove these curly braces from the environment variable, printing it like this instead:
{code}
abcd12-4321-ffff-a234-1111111111aa
{code}

Currently, we have an api end point to exclude commits with respect to a particular branch
{code:java}
https://api.bitbucket.org/2.0/repositories/<workspace_name>/<repo_name>/commits/<branch_name>?exclude=<branch_name>
example:  GET /repositories/{workspace}/{repo_slug}/commits/dev?exclude=master
{code}
But we do not have an API to exclude merged commits, an operation that is similar to the following git command.
{code:java}
git log --no-merges
{code}
It would be helpful in eliminating the duplicate file commits.

Currently, when pushing more than 5 tags, bookmarks, or branches at the same time, Pipelines will not trigger any builds and will return the following error message:
{panel}
Seems like you're running a lot of pipelines at the same time. This is usually due to an accidental push. To conserve your minutes, we won't run them all.
{panel}

This is a known limitation, as mentioned here:
{panel}
https://support.atlassian.com/bitbucket-cloud/docs/limitations-of-bitbucket-pipelines/
{panel}

This feature request is to add the ability for users to manually opt-out of this protection.

The review process of a Pull Request in Bitbucket is painful. I took a long time to add comments to PR, just to if some file is renamed by example, or some change move the code to far place in file, the comments becomes "outdated", and the reviewer and the coder needs hunts the the comments to check if it is valid yet.

It looks an interesting concept, but in the review process, is far more important go through each single previous comment and check if it was addressed (instead of re-read all the source code). I want firstly check if the coder answered and fixed my comments, and then review the new code if any.

This is so annoying... I took the habit of after post some comment, save the link for this comments, so it is "outdated", I can easily back to it. It is ridiculous save a comment list in notepad because of so bad UI experience of Bitbucket.

Yeah, I know we have this "Activity" sidebar, but this looks like a second-class citizen in the PR experience. Do you have tried scroll this thing? We are obligued to scroll using mouse! The scrollbar will scroll the full page only... Search something? NO, you can only filter. If you try search with browser's CTRL+F you need have some luck of the text is not trimmed...

So, what is the minimal experience we expect?
 # *Comment Centric Review Experience*, where we can see the all the comment list in full page, with appropriated scroll, paging, etc;
 # "Outdated" comments *cannot disappear or hide*, please put them in same order we have added, just mark them with a (soft) flag. I myself will mark as outdated or obsolete;
 # If you insist on "Outdated" comments, then at least when viewing this comment, by default *show the original version diff with the current one* when possible or empty panel when not;
 # Marking Files as Reviewed, or better, let us mark *individual Comments* as reviewed;
 # *Easily expose links for comments*, so we can ask direct feedback about them. (I know you already expose it, just make easier and clearer)

The Bitbucket should have an in-built feature to delete the files from the history. 

Currently, Bitbucket does 't support any in-built feature to delete the file history. As a workaround, the user needs to use BFG repo clear for that purpose.

edit by @mtizotti: History rewrite should also include the ability to perform *git resets* through the UI;
